<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"level":1,"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(32px,4vw,48px)"}}} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(32px,4vw,48px)">Local SEO in Rome: how to stand out in the capital of services</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="margin:8px 0 8px"><img src="/wp-content/themes/remarka-studio/assets/img/blog/seo-roma-cover.svg" alt="Local SEO in Rome: the map with the first three results a customer sees when searching «near me» in the capital" width="1200" height="630" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;border:1px solid var(--sr-bordo)"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:html -->
</section>
<!-- /wp:group -->
<!-- wp:group {"tagName":"section","className":"sr-section","layout":{"type":"constrained","contentSize":"1440px"}} -->
<section class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained sr-section"><!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch">A law firm in Parioli, a physiotherapist in San Giovanni, a B&B a stone’s throw from the Colosseum: in Rome each of them competes with another twenty within a one-kilometre radius. And when someone searches «accountant near me» or «hotel Rome centre» from their phone, they don’t scroll through ten pages of results — they look at the first three on the map and choose there. Local SEO in Rome is the discipline that decides who ends up in those three spots. It’s not magic nor a matter of budget: it’s work made of precise signals that almost nobody looks after all the way. Let’s see how it really works in the capital of services, what weighs in the ranking and where to start.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">Why in Rome local SEO is a contest of services<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Rome isn’t the city of manufacturing: it’s the capital of services, of the professions and of tourism. The province has over 444,000 registered businesses — of which more than 190,000 in services alone, according to the Rome Chamber of Commerce — and this changes the rules of the online game. Here the website isn’t a brochure: it’s the reception desk, the first quote, the first impression. And whoever sells a service stakes everything on trust and proximity, exactly the two things local SEO puts into play.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">On top of this comes tourism: Rome recorded 51.4 million overnight stays in 2024, an all-time record. For every B&B, restaurant or guide, appearing when a tourist searches from their phone «where to eat near Trastevere» is worth more than ten campaigns. Being found for «lawyer Rome» in a generic sense does little if you don’t show up when someone, two metro stops away, is searching right at that moment. Local SEO doesn’t aim for first place nationwide: it aims to be the most relevant to whoever is nearby, now.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">The local pack: the three spots that are worth gold in Rome<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The battlefield has a precise name: the «local pack», that block with the map and three businesses that Google shows at the top of results with local intent. Below it are the classic links, but the eye — especially on mobile — falls there. In a city as crowded as Rome, getting into those three boxes is worth more than ten organic positions: it’s the storefront the customer sees before anything else.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Google is unusually explicit about how it chooses who to show. In its official guide to local ranking it points to three factors — relevance, distance and prominence — and they’re worth knowing because you can work on all three. You don’t control the distance from whoever is searching, but you can help it along with an exact address and a declared service area; relevance and prominence, on the other hand, are built.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="margin:36px 0 8px"><img src="/wp-content/themes/remarka-studio/assets/img/blog/seo-roma-schema.svg" alt="The three factors of local SEO in Rome according to Google: relevance, distance and prominence, which decide the local pack" width="1200" height="500" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;border:1px solid var(--sr-bordo)"/><figcaption class="sr-mono" style="margin-top:12px;font-size:12.5px;letter-spacing:0.04em;color:var(--sr-grigio);max-width:75ch">The three factors Google uses to decide the local pack: relevance (how well the profile matches the search), distance (how close you are to the searcher) and prominence (how well known you are, reviews included). You can work on all three. Source: Google, official guide to local ranking.</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">The Google profile and reviews: the storefront before the website<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The engine of local SEO is your Google profile (Google Business Profile): it’s what appears on the map, with name, hours, photos, phone and reviews. For many local searches the customer decides looking at that alone, without ever opening the site. Looking after it isn’t a detail, it’s the foundation: an incomplete profile or one with wrong hours cuts you out of the relevant results before the competition even does.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">And then there are reviews, which weigh on trust and ranking together. According to BrightLocal’s annual consumer survey, almost everyone reads reviews before choosing a local business — and in Rome, with an international audience too, the ones in English count as well. It doesn’t mean inventing them, that would be a boomerang as well as a violation: it means asking for them methodically from those who had a good experience.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="https://support.google.com/business/answer/7091" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google — guide to local ranking →</a></p><p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/blog/google-business-profile-guide/">Read also: Google Business Profile, the storefront nobody tends →</a></p>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">The website still matters: structured data and Rome-specific content<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The Google profile doesn’t live alone: it leans on your website, and a well-kept site reinforces everything else. The first brick is structured data — that block of code, invisible to the visitor, that tells Google «this is a local business, here are its name, address, hours and area». It’s the LocalBusiness type from schema.org, and Google reads it to understand and better display your profile. The golden rule is consistency: name, address and phone identical wherever they appear, on the site and on directories.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">Then come contents that really speak of the territory. Not «Rome keywords» repeated by force, but pages that answer real local questions: the neighbourhoods you serve — Prati, the EUR, Parioli —, the cases followed in the city, the response times across the province. It’s technical SEO and content work together, and it’s exactly what we deliver as standard. Before adding a single line, though, it’s worth measuring the signals your site already sends Google.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
<p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/services/technical-seo/">Structured data and technical SEO in every site →</a></p><p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="/en/tools/eeat-signals/">Measure your home page’s E-E-A-T signals and structured data for free →</a></p><p class="sr-card-link" style="margin-top:14px"><a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/structured-data/intro-structured-data" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google — structured data and LocalBusiness →</a></p>
<!-- /wp:html -->
<!-- wp:heading {"style":{"typography":{"fontSize":"clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)"}}} -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,2.6vw,32px)">Where to start, in Rome and across the province<span class="sr-accent-dot">.</span></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">The right order is counter-intuitive: first the Google profile (complete, verified, with genuine reviews), then the site (structured data, consistent NAP data, local content), and finally prominence (citations and authoritative links, which come with time). Skipping the first step to chase the third is the most common mistake, and the most expensive. In Rome, where competitors already look after at least the profile, the game is played on the details the others neglect.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:paragraph {"fontSize":"base"} -->
<p class="has-base-font-size" style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.75;max-width:75ch;margin-top:16px">This work we do where the clients are: in Rome we have a real office, on Via Flaminia, and the first meeting — at your place or ours — is free. But the method is the same across the whole province: we analyse the current profile and site, we tell you what’s missing in black and white, and we work to get you into that map. Local SEO we build from the technical base, not with tricks.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
<!-- wp:html -->
